# mermaid-pro


# Mermaid Pro: Robust Diagramming Practices

As an expert in diagram generation, your goal is to create Mermaid schemas that are robust, error-free, and universally compatible across different markdown parsers, browser extensions, and built-in IDE previewers.

Many Mermaid parsers are extremely sensitive to whitespace and inline shorthand. You MUST follow these best practices to guarantee diagram stability.

## 1. Disable HTML Labels (The "Magic Bullet" for Strict Parsers)

By default, Mermaid attempts to parse node text as HTML labels, which often causes catastrophic rendering failures when text contains complex characters, quotes, or line breaks (`\n`). You MUST disable HTML labels globally using an initialization directive at the very top of your diagram.

**✅ GOOD:**

```mermaid
%%{init: { "flowchart": { "htmlLabels": false } }}%%
flowchart TD
    A["Line 1 \n Line 2"]
```

## 2. Avoid Inline Styling Shorthands

The most common cause of parse errors is the inline styling shorthand (`:::className`). 

**❌ BAD (Prone to parse errors):**

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    Start([Start Process]) ::: myStyle
```

**✅ GOOD (Decoupled styling):**

Always declare styles using `classDef` and apply them at the **end** of the flowchart using the `class` keyword.

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    %% Nodes
    Start([Start Process])
    End([End Process])

    %% Styling Definitions
    classDef processStyle fill:#e1f5fe,stroke:#01579b,stroke-width:1px;

    %% Applying Classes
    class Start,End processStyle
```

## 3. Quoting Node Text, Subgraphs, and Edge Connectors

Any text containing special characters, spaces, slashes (`/`), colons (`:`), or parentheses MUST be enclosed in double quotes. This applies strictly to:
1. **Node Text**: e.g., `A["Update DB (User Table)"]`
2. **Subgraph Titles**: e.g., `subgraph "Fase 1: Extracción y Limpieza"`
3. **Edge/Connector Labels**: e.g., `A -- "Fallo de Red o 429" --> B`

Failure to quote edge connectors with spaces or slashes is a leading cause of parse errors.

**❌ BAD (Unquoted text):**

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    A[Update DB (User Table)] --> B[Trigger Event-A]
```

**❌ BAD (Spaces inside the bracket and quote):**
Some strict visualizers will fail if there are spaces between the bracket and the quote.
```mermaid
flowchart TD
    A([ "Start" ])
```

**✅ GOOD:**

Always use double quotes inside the shape brackets if there are any non-alphanumeric characters, and **never put spaces between the bracket and the quote**.

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    A["Update DB (User Table)"] --> B["Trigger Event-A"]
    C(["Start"])
```

## 3. No HTML Tags in Node Labels

Many markdown-to-Mermaid renderers sanitize or fail on raw HTML.
Use native Mermaid newline characters (`\n`) instead of `<br>` or `<p>`.

**❌ BAD:**

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    A["Line 1 <br> Line 2"]
```

**✅ GOOD:**

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    A["Line 1 \n Line 2"]
```

## 4. Entity-Relationship (ER) Diagrams

When creating `erDiagram`s, follow these rules:

- **Order**: Define Entities `{ ... }` first, then Relationships `||--||` second.
- **Mandatory Labels**: In many Mermaid versions, every relationship MUST have a label. Ensure every relationship line ends with `: "label text"`. Failure to do this will cause an `Expecting COLON` error.
- **Zero Indentation**: Always start the diagram type and relationship lines at the very beginning of the line (zero indentation).
- Ensure spaces around relationships (e.g., `||--o{`).
- Keep attribute definitions strictly on one line per attribute.
- **CRITICAL**: Always end the code block with a blank line after the last diagram element.

**✅ GOOD:**

```mermaid
erDiagram
A {
    string ID
}
A ||--o{ B : "has"
A ||--o{ C : "links"

```

## 5. Whitespace and Code Block Isolation (The Double Newline Rule)

Many markdown renderers accidentally "bleed" the closing backticks (```) or the following markdown headers into the Mermaid parser. To prevent this:

- **ALWAYS** leave at least TWO empty lines BEFORE and AFTER the entire ` ```mermaid ` block.
- **ALWAYS** ensure the last character of the Mermaid code is a newline, followed by one more empty line *inside* the code block.

**❌ BAD (Causes "got '`'" error):**

```mermaid
erDiagram
    A {
    }```

**✅ GOOD:**

```mermaid
erDiagram
    A {
    }


```

## 6. Sequence Diagrams

For sequence diagrams, always use `autonumber` (optional but recommended for clarity) and explicitly define actors/participants before using them.

**✅ GOOD:**

```mermaid
sequenceDiagram
    participant U as User
    participant A as API
    
    U->>A: Request Data
    A-->>U: Return JSON
```

## 7. Compatibility with Standalone Tools (Markdown vs Raw)

Many official tools, including the **Mermaid Live Editor**, expect ONLY the Mermaid diagram code. They will fail if provided with an entire Markdown file containing headers, SQL, or other text.

- **For Documentation**: Use fenced blocks (```mermaid) inside `.md` files.
- **For External Tools**: Always provide a "Clean Export" or a standalone `.mmd` file containing only the raw Mermaid logic.
- **Troubleshooting**: If you see `No diagram type detected...`, it is likely because the parser is receiving markdown headers or non-mermaid text.

## 8. Semantic Color Coding for Flowcharts

To ensure diagrams are visually intuitive and consistent across workflows, ALWAYS apply standard semantic color coding to nodes based on their nature.

> [!WARNING]
> Many markdown viewers, IDE previewers, and sanitizers strip out `<style>` sheets or ignore `classDef`/`class` declarations. To guarantee that colors are rendered correctly in all environments, ALWAYS use explicit, inline `style` declarations for each node at the bottom of the flowchart. Do NOT use `classDef` or `class`.

**Standard Color Palette Guidelines (Mermaid Live Editor Compatible Pastels):**
- **Start/End Nodes**: `fill:#E8F5E9,stroke:#81C784,color:#2E7D32,stroke-width:2px`
- **Warnings / Errors / Exceptions / Fallbacks**: `fill:#FFF3E0,stroke:#FFB74D,color:#E65100,stroke-width:2px`
- **Core Processes / Standard Actions**: `fill:#E3F2FD,stroke:#64B5F6,color:#1565C0,stroke-width:2px`
- **Important Validations / Business Rules**: `fill:#F3E5F5,stroke:#BA68C8,color:#6A1B9A,stroke-width:2px`
- **Databases / Storage / External Systems**: `fill:#ECEFF1,stroke:#90A4AE,color:#37474F,stroke-width:2px`

> [!IMPORTANT]
> Do NOT include comments (`%%`) or blank lines interspersed within or around your `style` declarations at the end of the file. Group all `style` declarations together tightly. Adding comments or whitespace between styles causes parser failures in Mermaid Live Editor.

**Example:**
```mermaid
flowchart TD
    StartNode(["Start"]) --> ActionNode["Process"]
    ActionNode --> ErrorNode{"Error?"}
    ErrorNode -- "Yes" --> EndNode(["End"])

    style StartNode fill:#E8F5E9,stroke:#81C784,color:#2E7D32,stroke-width:2px
    style EndNode fill:#E8F5E9,stroke:#81C784,color:#2E7D32,stroke-width:2px
    style ActionNode fill:#E3F2FD,stroke:#64B5F6,color:#1565C0,stroke-width:2px
    style ErrorNode fill:#FFF3E0,stroke:#FFB74D,color:#E65100,stroke-width:2px
```

## 9. Enforcement Checklist

1. **Did I include `%%{init: { "flowchart": { "htmlLabels": false } }}%%` at the very top?**
2. **Did I use `flowchart TD` instead of `graph TD`?**
3. Did I remove all `:::` inline styles and use explicit `style NodeID fill:#...` declarations at the bottom?
4. Are all node labels, subgraph titles, and edge connectors with spaces or special characters enclosed in `" "` quotes?
5. Are all line breaks using `\n` instead of HTML?
6. **Do all ER relationships have mandatory labels (e.g., `: "label")?**
7. **Are there blank lines before/after the code block?**
8. **Is the Mermaid code block clean of any indentation?**
9. **Is there a standalone `.mmd` version if using external/official tools?**
